{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0bfa3bc-5905-4c19-91c1-396e08c1b714","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01GWoFDzoPX3Y3tqy5bjXebE","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Implementing ticket classifier"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_014rCQSKH2DPUJpF4sUfWaqT","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-65d98091af744647ae71ce40be2ce906/TicketClassifier && mkdir -p Models Services Controllers","description":"Create project directories"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create project directories"}],"interactionId":"b5670fb1-6a55-418f-9c93-d9a8f3710571","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have the full picture. Let me build the implementation:\n\n1. Add ML.NET NuGet package\n2. Create Models (TicketData, TicketPrediction)\n3. Create a TicketModelTrainer service that trains the model and provides evaluation metrics\n4. Create a PredictionController with endpoints for training, evaluating, and predicting\n5. Wire it all up in Program.cs\n\nLet me implement this step by step.\n\nThe data has:\n- Subject (string)\n- Description (string) \n- Priority (int 1-3)\n- Category (string) - one of: Billing, Technical, General\n\n\nThis is a multiclass classification problem, so I'll use ML.NET's text featurization to process the Subject and Description fields, then combine that with Priority as a numeric feature. I'll organize the code across Models, Services, and Controllers, then wire everything up in Program.cs.","outputTokens":421,"requestId":"5C33:165EF2:1C4254B:1F4BD6F:69FA8F7D"},"id":"44f709b0-a204-4a39-bb79-936c00e960a4","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:47:01.382Z","parentId":"9104a33e-3aee-4098-8629-2ddb04c87c9e"}
